# Quantum-Double-Slit-Simulation-de-Broglie-Interference-Model
A precise mathematical and physical simulation of the interference phenomenon observed in the double-slit experiment, based on the de Broglie wavelength hypothesis. This simulation bridges the gap between the wave-like quantum evolution of particles and the classical interference patterns characteristic of Fraunhofer diffraction.
Quantum Double-Slit Simulation: de Broglie Interference Model
Description
This project provides a rigorous mathematical and physical simulation of the interference phenomenon observed in the double-slit experiment, grounded in the de Broglie wavelength hypothesis. The simulation bridges the gap between the wave-like quantum evolution of particles and the classical interference patterns characterized by the Fraunhofer diffraction regime.
Key Features
Analytical Fidelity: Implements a high-precision probability density distribution function derived from quantum interference principles.
Visual Clarity: Integrates a spatial representation of the double-slit apparatus, allowing for clear correlation between the physical setup and the resulting diffraction pattern.
Performance-Oriented: A highly efficient Python-based model that offers rapid visualization of wave dynamics.
Requirements
Python 3.x
numpy
matplotlib
How to Run
Ensure you have the required libraries installed:
pip install numpy matplotlib
Run the main simulation script:
python double_slit_simulation.py
